Objective

Theory and Definitions

Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test: ADF (Augmented Dickey-Fuller) test is a statistical significance test which means the test will give results in hypothesis tests with null and alternative hypotheses. As a result, we will have a p-value from which we will need to make inferences about the time series, whether it is stationary or not. If P-value > 0.05, then the given dataset does not reject the H0 hypothesis, hence is non-stationary. Otherwise, the H0 hypothesis is rejected and the dataset turns out to be stationary.

Johansen Co-integration Test: Johansens test is a way to determine if three or more time series are cointegrated. More specifically, it assesses the validity of a cointegrating relationship, using a maximum likelihood estimates (MLE) approach. It is also used to find the number of relationships and as a tool to estimating those relationships. There are two types of Johansens test: one uses trace (from linear algebra), the other a maximum eigenvalue approach (an eigenvalue is a special scalar; When you multiply a matrix by a vector and get the same vector as an answer, along with a new scalar, the scalar is called an eigenvalue).

VECM: A vector error correction (VEC) model is a restricted VAR that has cointegration restrictions built into the specification, so that it is designed for use with nonstationary series that are known to be cointegrated. The VEC specification restricts the long-run behavior of the endogenous variables to converge to their cointegrating relationships while allowing a wide range of short-run dynamics. The cointegration term is known as the error correction term since the deviation from long-run equilibrium is corrected gradually through a series of partial short-run adjustments.

Granger Causality Test: Granger causality is a statistical concept of causality that is based on prediction. According to Granger causality, if a signal X1 "Granger-causes" (or "G-causes") a signal X2, then past values of X1 should contain information that helps predict X2 above and beyond the information contained in past values of X2 alone. Its mathematical formulation is based on linear regression modeling of stochastic processes (Granger 1969). More complex extensions to nonlinear cases exist, however these extensions are often more difficult to apply in practice.

Augmented Dickey Fuller Test Function

In [ ]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller

def ADF_test(data):
    ST = adfuller(data, autolag = 'AIC')
    print('ADF: ', ST[0])
    print('P-value: ', ST[1])
    print('No. of Lags: ', ST[2])
    print('No. of observations used: ', ST[3])
    print('Critical Values: ')
    for item, value in ST[4].items():
        print('\t', item, ': ', value)
    
    return ST[1]

Co-integration Test

In this segment, we perform cointegration tests. This test is conducted since all variables are I1 type stationary, thus, we can employ the Cointegration Test through ADF Statistics on the spreads.

Let Y, X be the parameters undergoing cointegration test. There exists a such that, Spread = Y - .X is stationary. Then we can conclude that Y and X are cointegrated.

In [ ]:
def customOLS(x,y):
    model = sm.OLS(y,x)
    result = model.fit()
    # print(result.summary())

    return result.params[0]
In [ ]:
for i in range(len(tsData.columns)):
    for j in range(i):

        print(tsData.columns[i], ' and ', tsData.columns[j])
        betaV = customOLS(tsData[tsData.columns[i]],tsData[tsData.columns[j]])
        print('Beta: ', betaV)

        spreadV = tsData[tsData.columns[j]] - betaV * tsData[tsData.columns[i]]
        plt.plot(spreadV)
        plt.draw()
        plt.show()
        
        Stationarity_res = ADF_test(spreadV)

        if Stationarity_res > 0.05 :
            print('\nThe given dataset does not reject H0 hypothesis, hence is non-stationary.')
            print(tsData.columns[i], ' and ', tsData.columns[j], 'are not co-integrated.\n')
        else:
            print('\nThe given dataset rejects H0 hypothesis, hence is stationary.')
            print(tsData.columns[i], ' and ', tsData.columns[j], 'are co-integrated.\n')

Johansen Test

In the previous segment, we were unable to obtain satisfactory conclusions of Cointegration tests from ADF Statistics applied on the spreads. Therefore, we deploy Johansen Test in this segment to obtain the necessary rank.

from statsmodels.tsa.vector_ar.vecm import select_coint_rank

print('Co-integration Rank: ', rank_test.rank)

Conclusion

In this assignment we tested for normality, stationarity and used statistical methods such as VECM and Granger Causality to find relationships among macro-economic variables obtained from RBI Database. During the ADF Test, all the parameters CIC, NFE, CL & NML were determined to be non-stationary. After I1 type differencing, we obtained stationary resuts from the parameters. We further obtained the Lag Order from AIC Statistics. We conducted the co-integration test in a manual fashion by applying ADF tests over spreads obtained from each pair of parameters. The results were non-comprehensible, hence, we conducted Johansen Co-integration Test and obtained the cointegration rank directly. We used the lag and rank obtained from the previous tests to feed our VEC Model for training with our macro-economic parameters. Thus, we were able to establish and explain long-term relationship among those parameters by forecasting 100 data-points into the future. The Granger Causality Test revealed that there does not exist any Granger-cause between the parameters, other than NFE nad CL which rejected H0 hypothesis at 5% significance level. Hence, it can be concluded that VEC Model is a fit to accurately establish and explain long-term relationship among macro-econimic variables.
